Recap

  • Minerals: a substance must meet the following criteria to be classified as a mineral:
    1. Naturally occurring: Formed by natural processes without human intervention.
    2. Inorganic: Not produced by biological processes.
    3. Solid: Must exist in a solid state under normal Earth conditions.
    4. Definite chemical composition: Has a specific chemical formula.
    5. Crystalline structure: Atoms are arranged in an orderly and repeating pattern.
  • What are atoms?

Atomic Structure

  • Atom: The basic unit of matter, consisting of a nucleus surrounded by electrons.
  • Nucleus: The atomâs core, containing protons and neutrons.
  • Electrons: Negatively charged particles orbiting the nucleus in electron shells.

Electron Configuration

  • Electron Configuration: Determines bonding and properties

Bonding Forces in Crystals (1)

  • Ionic Bond
    • Ionic bonds form, for example, between sodium (Na) and chlorine (Cl) in NaCl.
    • Electrons are transferred from sodium to chlorine.
    • This transfer creates positively charged sodium ions (Naâº) and negatively charged chloride ions (Clâ»).
    • The electrostatic attraction between Naâº and Clâ» holds the compound together.
    • Key properties of ionic compounds:
      • High melting and boiling points (due to strong ionic bonds).
      • Electrical conductivity when molten or dissolved (ions are free to move).

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Bonding Forces in Crystals (2)

  • Covalent Bond
    • Covalent bonds involve the sharing of electrons between atoms.
    • In diamond (C), each carbon atom shares four electrons with other carbon atoms.
    • This creates a strong, three-dimensional network of covalently bonded carbon atoms.
    • Key properties of covalent compounds:
      • High hardness and melting point (due to strong covalent bonds in the structure).
      • Non-conductive (no free electrons to carry an electrical charge).

Source: https://www.uyir.at

Bonding Forces in Crystals (3)

  • Metallic Bond
    • Metallic elements have loosely held outer electrons.
    • Free movement of electrons occurs when bonds form between metal atoms.
    • Formation: Delocalized electron sea
    • This structure explains two key properties of metals:
      • Electrical conductivity (free electrons allow current to flow).
      • Malleability (metals can be deformed and shaped easily).
    • Example: Copper (Cu)

Source: https://geo.libretexts.org/

Bonding Forces in Crystals (4)

  • Van der Waals Bond
    • the bond is a weak, non-covalent interaction between molecules or within parts of a molecule, arising from temporary dipoles or induced charges.
    • Graphite consists of layers of carbon atoms bonded covalently within each layer.
    • Between these layers, Van der Waals forces hold the layers together.
    • These are weak attractions caused by temporary dipoles between adjacent layers.
    • This structure gives graphite its unique properties:
      • Slippery and soft (layers can easily slide over each other).
      • Good electrical conductor (electrons can move freely within layers).

Source: Poulla, Kalotina. (2019)

Unit Cell, Crystal Lattice, and Coordination Number

  • Unit Cell:
    The smallest repeating structure in a crystal. It contains atoms arranged in a specific pattern and, when repeated, forms the entire crystal.

  • Crystal Lattice:
    A 3D arrangement of unit cells that repeat in space. It defines the overall symmetry and physical properties of the crystal.

  • Coordination Number:
    The number of nearest neighboring atoms surrounding a central atom in a crystal structure. It reflects the density and arrangement of atoms in the crystal lattice.

  • Key concept:
    Crystals are composed of unit cells that repeat in space, forming a crystal lattice, with coordination number determining atomic packing.

Source: https://www.britannica.com
